Paper name: Estimating the costs of consumer-facing cybercrime: A tailored instrument and representative data for six EU countries
Description: We develop an instrument to measure the prevalence of cybercrime and the costs to consumers. We collected representative data for adult Internet users in the following six European member states (in protocol order): Germany (DE), Estonia (EE), Italy (IT), the Netherlands (NL), Poland (PL), and the United Kingdom (UK).

Paper name: International Comparison of Bank Fraud Reimbursement: Customer Perceptions and Contractual Terms
Description: We surveyed the terms and conditions of 30 banks operating in 25 countries. The terms and conditions were reviewed to identify instructions or advice on security. This included how users should handle the PINs associated with their cards, as well as telephone and Internet banking credentials. The documents are worked through by 151 participants.

Paper name: Consumer Attitudes Toward Data Breach Notifications and Loss of Personal Information
Description: The survey was conducted using the American Life Panel, a nationally representative panel of more than 6,000 adults who participate in Internet-based surveys covering a diverse set of issues. Fielded between May 15 and June 1, 2015, the survey was designed to provide a snapshot of the frequency of breach notifications and the types of data compromised, as well as consumer reactions to the breach, the notification process, and the affected company. Our survey was fielded between May 14 and June 1, 2015, to 2,618 adults.
